[2] India (New Delhi)
Date: Fri 27 Jun 2008
Source: Times of India [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Cities/First_dengue_death_reported_in_Delhi/articleshow/3171781.cms>


A woman has died of dengue at a hospital in the 1st fatal case due to
the disease in the capital this year [2008].

"The present climate, which is between 28 to 30 deg.C with high humidity,
is conducive to breeding of the _Aedes_ mosquito," said Bir Singh,
professor of community medicine at the All India Institute of Medical
Sciences (AIIMS). "This particular climate helps them thrive and
transmit the disease. But once temperatures start dipping down from
November, the mosquito dies."

A total of 550 dengue cases and one death were reported in Delhi last
year [2007]. According to MCD [Municipal Corporation of Delhi], the
rains have resulted in an increase in mosquito breeding. The
department claims to be holding regular meetings with resident
welfare associations of the 272 wards and NGOs [non-governmental
organizations] to create awareness about the disease. The MCD has
also been educating teachers and children in primary schools about
precautionary measures.

Temephos, an insecticide that can help prevent breeding of the
_Aedes_ mosquito, is being distributed free of cost by MCD [Temephos
at one percent is used in containers of non-potable water for control
of _Aedes aegypti_ larvae and pupae. Periodic reapplication is
required for long-term control. Other control measures are required
for control of breeding sites in water for human use. - Mod.TY].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

A map of India showing the location of New Delhi can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/india_pol01.jpg>.
