[7] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Thu 19 Jun 2008
Source: Gazeta Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://gazetaonline.globo.com/noticias/minutoaminuto/nacional/nacional_materia.php?cd_matia=448823&cd_site=843>


In Bahia, 32 cities declared a state of alert due to dengue and
exactly when the number of cases should be falling.

Since the beginning of the year [2008], 900 cases of dengue were
recorded in Itabuna, in southern Bahia. In several places, the
[government] agents found much garbage and uncovered [water] tanks
[breeding sites for the _Aedes_ dengue virus vector mosquito. -
Mod.TY].

In Presidente Dutra [town], in central-west Bahia, for every 5
residents, one already has had the disease. In 2008, more than 30 000
cases were recorded throughout the state, representing an increase of
over 224 percent in relation to the same period of last year [2007].

The 32 cities that are in a state of alert recorded the most severe
cases of the disease. This year [2008], 6 people died of DHF in Bahia.

According to Epidemiological Surveillance, the failure to fight
[dengue] outbreaks during the summer has allowed the rain of recent
weeks to provoke a rapid proliferation of mosquitoes and disease
[dengue virus transmission], in a time when the number of cases should
be decreasing.

In Salvador [the state capital], the situation is no different. The
strike of health workers last year [2007] and early this year [2008]
stopped the work on combating outbreaks of mosquitoes that transmit
the virus, which has spread. From the beginning of the year [2008]
until now [mid-June 2008], 1900 dengue cases were recorded [in
Salvador]. More than half the cases were concentrated in 4 districts,
and the health posts continue full.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[A map showing the location of Bahia and the cities and town
mentioned in this report can be accessed at:
<http://www.maplandia.com/brazil/bahia/>.
- Mod.TY]
